<br>
Why?<br>
<br>
Because there's not a chance in hell that the planes will be available when I can get a group together.  I don't put together raids of 18 level 60s.  I put together raids of 35 people with an average level of low 50s.  To do so, it includes virtually every planar-level character in both Horizons and Sigils (we dual-book), plus some friends.<br>
<br>
We rearrange our RL schedules to do this.  And they aren't going to be so excited about it when I say, &quot;Oh, and then we'll spend 2 hours figuring out where we can go.&quot;  Why should they rearrange their schedules like this, then?  Answer: a lot of them won't.<br>
<br>
There are a LOT of people who want a scheduled system.  An unwillingness to compromise is selfish.<br>
<br>
Maybe you don't remember a certain druid in Cult of the Red Dragon a while ago.  You and Joshore used to hunt spectres in OOT, back when the level limit was 50.  You weren't grouped -- Joshore was pulling for his group, you were soloing.<br>
<br>
One day, Joshore got very frustrated sharing limited spawn.  You chatted with him, and the message was basically, &quot;What happened to the nice druid who I could get along with?&quot;<br>
<br>
And now I'm asking the same thing.  What happened to the nice enchanter I used to get along with, who taught me a little something about compromise?<br>
